OpenCV Tutorial¶

This notebook exposes the basic operations available with the open source computer vision library OpenCV.

/content/opencv-logo2.png

OpenCV goals:

  • Advance vision research by providing not only open but also optimized code for basic vision infrastructure. No more reinventing the wheel.
  • Disseminate vision knowledge by providing a common infrastructure that developers could build on, so that code would be more readily readable and transferable.
  • Advance vision-based commercial applications by making portable, performance-optimized code available for free – with a license that did not require code to be open or free itself.

https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenCV

Matrix indexing¶

Slicing¶

Slicing operator is a very useful operation for working with matrices and vectors. This is a python native operation when it is applied to lists, but it is extended to numpy matrices and vectors, where they are very efficient.

This operation is applied to an existing vector/matrix to create a new instance from the original (https://www.tutorialsteacher.com/python/slice-method). The syntax of the operation is as follows:

arr[start:stop:step]

Where:

  • arr: Vector where we are applying the operation.
  • start: Index of the arr element which we want to be the first element of the new vector. By default is 0.
  • stop: Index of the arr element which we want to be the last element of the new vector.
  • step: How we want to iterate arr to create the new vector. By default is 1

Next we will see the operator behaviour with some examples:

Segmenting red gloves using basic operations¶

In [53]:
im_guant = cv2.imread("hoi_0000132.png")
im_guant = cv2.cvtColor(im_guant, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
plt.imshow(im_guant);

First of all, I will segment my objective and I will use the image without background

In [54]:
im_guant_noBG = cv2.imread("/content/hoi_0000132_noBackground.png")
im_guant_noBG = cv2.cvtColor(im_guant_noBG, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
plt.imshow(im_guant_noBG);

Now I will grayscale tha image and see how much the gloves will look.

In [57]:
im_guant_noBG_G = cv2.cvtColor(im_guant_noBG,cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
plt.imshow(im_guant_noBG_G, cmap = "gray");

As it can see, the gloves are in the same tone as the much part of the rest of te image, for example the hoodie.

To try something different, I will use the HSV. Using this color model can bring me the option to represent better the red colour in the image due to the channels.

In [60]:
im_guant_HSV = cv2.cvtColor(im_guant_noBG, cv2.COLOR_RGB2HSV)
plt.imshow(im_guant_HSV);

Now it can see how the gloves can see different as in the RGB and greyscaled image. For the next step, I will define the range of red colour.

Red can have two ranges in HSV due to the way the hue is structured. So, I will need two masks and then combine them.

The hue component in the HSV color space for OpenCV ranges between 0 to 180. Within this range, the color red is located at the extremes. Specifically, it resides between 0-10 and 160-180. I will use the cv2.inRange() function to create binary masks. This function segments an image based on specified lower and upper bounds. Pixels falling within these bounds are set to white (255), while all other pixels are set to black (0).

Since red spans two separate intervals in the hue channel, we need two distinct masks (mask1 & mask2). After generating them, we combine these masks to get a comprehensive binary representation of all red regions in the image.

In [61]:
# Ranges for the red color
lower_red_1 = np.array([0, 100, 100])
upper_red_1 = np.array([10, 255, 255])

lower_red_2 = np.array([160, 100, 100])
upper_red_2 = np.array([180, 255, 255])

# Masks to detect red
mask1 = cv2.inRange(im_guant_HSV, lower_red_1, upper_red_1)
mask2 = cv2.inRange(im_guant_HSV, lower_red_2, upper_red_2)

# Combine the masks
combined_mask = mask1 + mask2

Once the ranges are defined for the red color, and created the masks to detect the red colour, I combined the masks

In [64]:
result = cv2.bitwise_and(im_guant_HSV, im_guant_HSV, mask=combined_mask)
plt.imshow(result)
Out[64]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x7f9cc8c6f820>

These masks helped to identify the gloves to segment them of the rest of the image. That is because separate of hue from brightness and saturation in HSV offers consistent color identification, irrespective of lighting variations. This is especially advantageous for distinguishing colors like red, ensuring accurate detection of objects like the gloves, even under diverse lighting conditions
